  "prompt": "How can I change the \"Ok Google\" phrase to something else in a Nexus 6?",
  "response": "Unfortunately, **you cannot directly change the \"Ok Google\" hotword to something else on a Nexus 6 or any other Android device running Google Assistant/Google Now.** This feature used to be available in older versions of Android (pre-Google Assistant), but it has been removed.\n\nHere's why and what you can do:\n\n* **Google's Control:** Google controls the hotword activation for Google Assistant.  They've standardized it to \"Ok Google\" (or \"Hey Google\") to ensure consistent performance and recognition across all devices.\n\n* **Third-Party Apps Are Limited:** While there are third-party apps that claim to offer custom voice commands, they generally aren't reliable replacements for the core \"Ok Google\" functionality. They often:\n    * **Require constant running in the background:** This can drain battery life.\n    * **May not be as accurate:** Their voice recognition might not be as robust as Google's.\n    * **May not work seamlessly:**  They might not integrate well with all your phone's features.\n    * **Raise privacy concerns:**  Be cautious about giving third-party apps access to your microphone and data.\n\n**What you CAN do:**\n\n1. **Improve \"Ok Google\" Recognition:**\n\n   * **Retrain your voice model:** Go to **Google App > Menu > Settings > Voice > Ok Google Detection** and retrain the voice model. Speak clearly and in different environments to improve accuracy.\n   * **Ensure \"From any screen\" is enabled:** In the same settings, make sure \"From any screen\" is turned on so that the hotword detection works even when your phone is locked.\n\n2. **Use Alternative Launch Methods:**\n\n   * **Tap the Google Assistant icon:** If voice activation isn't working well for you, you can always manually launch Google Assistant by tapping the microphone icon in the Google Search bar or by long-pressing the home button (if configured).\n   * **Shortcuts/Widgets:**  Create a shortcut or widget on your home screen that directly launches Google Assistant.\n\n3. **Explore Android Accessibility Features (For Specific Needs):**\n\n   * Android has accessibility features that can help with voice control, but these aren't designed for replacing the \"Ok Google\" hotword.  They are primarily for users with disabilities.\n\n**In summary, while you can't change the hotword itself, focus on improving its recognition and using alternative launch methods for the Google Assistant.**  Be very wary of third-party apps promising this functionality, as they are often unreliable and potentially risky.\n",
